ured; a cash-rich firm can show low D/E yet still be risky elsewhere."},{"label":"Earnings momentum","value":-48.67,"unit":"% YoY","status":"weak","read":"Profit down 49% YoY (latest TTM).","meaning":"Trailing-twelve-month net profit vs the year-ago TTM (and whether the YoY rate is rising = 'accelerating').","why_useful":"Improving, accelerating earnings tend to drive re-rating; falling profit warns of a deteriorating business.","why_it_can_fail":"TTM can be lumpy for cyclicals/one-offs; cross-check the multi-year trend on the Fundamentals tab."}]},"valuation":{"ok":true,"is_bank":false,"pe_now":40.0,"pe_percentile":94.0,"median_pe":31.1,"earnings_yield_pct":2.5,"pb":2.11,"ev_ebitda":12.42,"quality_score":57.0,"pat_cagr_5y_pct":8.1,"peg":4.94,"cheapness":{"status":"weak","read":"P/E at the 94-percentile of its 10-yr range \u2014 expensive vs its own history."},"expectations":"At 40.0\u00d7 earnings for ~8% 5-yr profit CAGR, the market is paying \u22484.94\u00d7 growth (PEG). >2 = a lot already priced in; <1 = cheap if growth holds.","cyclical_caveat":null,"meaning":"P/E percentile = where today's price-to-earnings sits within the stock's own last-10-yr range (low = cheap vs its past). Paired with the Quality score and 5-yr profit growth so a cheap multiple is judged against business strength, not in isolation.","why_useful":"Cheapness only matters relative to quality and growth \u2014 a low P/E on a declining or peak-cyclical business is a trap, not a bargain.","why_it_can_fail":"P/E breaks for loss-makers / one-offs; for banks use P/B not EV/EBITDA; a multiple cheap vs history can stay cheap if the business has structurally de-rated."},"ownership":{"ok":true,"na":null,"holders":{"Promoter":{"periods":["Dec 2024","Mar 2025","Jun 2025","Sep 2025","Dec 2025","Mar 2026"],"values":[50.17,50.17,50.17,50.17,50.17,50.17],"latest_pct":50.17,"chg_1y_pp":0.0},"FII":{"periods":["Dec 2024","Mar 2025","Jun 2025","Sep 2025","Dec 2025","Mar 2026"],"values":[18.0,18.21,15.8,12.81,1